Introduction and data

Concerning the growing income and wealth inequality in the United States due to systemic discrimination, our group seek to investigate different factors that influence a personâs income. To narrow down the scope of inquiry, this research poses the question of whether there is a relationship between a personâs income, their educational background, and capital gain in the United States. Our hypothesis is that as the education level and capital gain of a person increases, their income will also increase.

The dataset we use was extracted by Barry Becker from the 1994 US Census Bureauâs database and was later donated to the Machine Learning Repository of University of California, Irvine Census Income Data Set. This dataset consists of 51 state samples, each with a different probability of selection, and contains 15 attributes, which include a personâs education level, race, capital gain and other relevant information. There are 32561 data set instances, with a mix of continuous and discrete data.

To test our hypothesis, we conducted proper data wrangling and set up control variables. We are using education, num_education and capital gain as key explanatory variables, and income as our outcome variable. We will also include marital status, occupation, race, sex and native country as control variables. These variables help us to account for income changes based on personâs marital status, the kind of work they do, their race, and sex.

In order to test our hypothesis, we begin by visualizing the relationship between the explanatory variables, namely education, capital gain, and the outcome variable income.

Results

Hypothesis Test

For the inferential analysis, our null hypothesis is that there is no association between income and education, and our alternative hypothesis is that there is an association between income and education.


    Pearson's Chi-squared test

data:  tab
X-squared = 4426.8, df = 8, p-value < 2.2e-16

This is a table of the Chi-Squared null distribution with 8 degrees of freedom. The red line marks the C statistic, and anything shaded to the right of the line is our p-value (which is not visible due to it being a low value).

Our group decided to use a chi-squared test because a couple of the variables we want to explore are both categorical variables that have more than one level. We first have to make sure that there are enough observations and that the variables are independently observedâ which are both fulfilled by our dataset. We first calculate the C statistic to serve as our value to run the chi-squared test on. Then, we load the data into R to get our chi-squared null distribution to see how likely we are to see our C statistic of 4427. We also displayed a p-value by shading in the area to the right of our observed C statistic and found that the p-value is below 2.2e-16. Since this p-value is negligible, we reject the null hypothesis. Hence, we can conclude that there is an association between income and education.

Interpretation from plots and tables

Figure 1 for years of education filled by income above supports our hypothesis that there is a relationship between years of education and income. According to the graph, as the number of years of education increases, the proportion of people having higher income increases as well.

In Figure 2, we can see that the capital gain for higher income level is more right skewed as compared to the capital gain for lower income level. This plot supports our hypothesis that capital gain is related to income because the vast majority of people who have a capital gain ranging from $500 all the way up to over $15000 are the ones making over $50k a year, and the people who have a capital gain amount lower than $500 are the ones who make less than $50k a year.

Figure 3 between education and income and the summary statistics table (Table 1) for proportions of income level for every education level also supports our hypothesis that education and income are related. That is to say, we can see that the proportions of those who make over $50k are higher when a personâs level of education is also higher.

Table 2 is the summary statistics for explanatory variables. Accordingly, it can be observed that for each education level, the mean, median and standard deviation for years of education and capital gain is generally higher for the income group of over $50k a year. This might indicate an interaction effect between education level and years of education.

Regression Analysis

The linear regression model (Table 3) shows that by keeping all the other variables baseline, when the level of education is higher, the probability of people being in a higher income group increases. Likewise, for every dollar increase in capital gain, the probability of people being in a higher income group increases by 0.0000083. Finally, for every year increase in years of education, the model predicts an increase of probability of 0.0138270 of people being in the higher income group. Since the slope for all of our explanatory variables are positive, there seems to be a positive linear relationship between our explanatory variables and outcome variables. However, as we plot the residual plot for our linear regression model, we observe that the relationship between our variables is not linear. This means while thereâs a relationship between our explanatory variables and outcome variables, there could be a better model other than the linear regression model to explain the relationship.

Conclusion

The observations from our plots, statistics table, linear regression model and hypothesis test show that thereâs a relationship between our explanatory variables: education, capital gain, years of education, and our outcome variable: income.

Discussions

Our statistical analysis verified the hypothesis that as the education level and capital gain of a person increases, their income will also increase.

Through the use of linear regression, hypothesis testing, and exploratory data analysis, we were able to produce results that suggest a general relationship between our observed variables, and even more so a positive predictive relationship.

However, we would like to point out some of the potential biases and flaws behind our statistical design. To begin with, the data we were able to extract was collected in 1996 â demographics of population and economic landscape since then have drastically changed in the United States. Factors such as inflation, policy changes on immigration, racial discrimination, etc, can make this dataset outdated. Hence, this research can only provide us a glimpse into the factors that influence a personâs income from two decades ago, and does not necessarily apply to present time. Also, our access to knowledge is limited in that we do not have the coding experience in order to properly compute non-linear models we need, as referenced previously on regression analysis.

Finally, we encourage future research on factors that influence a personâs accessibility to education, as our research findings suggest that education is a key indicator of income. Societal, systemic and structural discrimination tend to result in economic inequality, and we believe that understanding education (in)accessibility will shed light on our original purpose for this research, which is to investigate different factors that play a role in the growing wealth disparity in the United States.
